<h2 id=3D"features">Features</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Interactive affine encoder/decoder with multiplier and shift inputs=
.</li>
    <li>Supports 25+ languages and transcriptions.</li>
    <li>Shows allowed multipliers based on the selected alphabet.</li>
    <li>Shows overview of all letter translations based on the selected key=
s.</li>
    <li>Supports language and transcription choices and keeps spacing, punc=
tuation, and casing intact.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id=3D"what-is-the-affine-cipher">What is the Affine cipher</h2>
<p>The affine cipher is a form of substitution cipher where each letter in =
an alphabet is mapped to its numeric
    equivalent, encrypted using a simple mathematical function, and then co=
nverted back to a letter.</p>
<p>
    The mathematical formula is <code>E(x) =3D (ax + b) mod m</code>
    where <var>a</var> and <var>b</var> are secret parameters and <var>m</v=
ar> is the alphabet size. For example if we
    use a =3D 5 and b =3D 8 with the English alphabet (where
    <var>A =3D 0</var>, <var>B =3D 1</var>, ..., <var>Z =3D 25</var>), then=
 the encryption function would be:
</p>
<pre><code>
    E(x) =3D (5x + 8) mod 26
</code></pre>
<p>
    This means the letter C (which is 2) would be encrypted as:
</p>
<pre><code>
    E(2) =3D (5 =C3=97 2 + 8) mod 26 =3D 18 mod 26 =3D 18
</code></pre>
<p>
    And 18 corresponds to the letter S, so C maps to S.
</p>
<p>
    The choice of <var>a</var> must be coprime to <var>m</var> (the size of=
 the alphabet). This ensures that each letter
    maps uniquely to another letter, allowing for proper decryption.
</p>

<h2 id=3D"usage">Usage</h2>
<p>
    Affine ciphers appear in puzzle hunts, geocaching mysteries, and classr=
oom exercises about modular arithmetic. When
    decoding, look for sensible language, and remember that some puzzles re=
move spaces or punctuation to add a little extra misdirection.
</p>


